uments not yet available in English, Carbone demonstrates both that Merleau-Ponty's interest in film was sustained and philosophically crucial, and also that his thinking provides an important resource for illuminating our contemporary relationship to images, with profound implications for the future of philosophy and aesthetics. Building on his earlier work on Marcel Proust and considering ongoing developments in optical and media technologies, Carbone adds his own philosophical insight into understanding the visual today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion pictures. 0aPainting. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Aesthetics. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh1 aNijhuis, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845880940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438458809423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438458809/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles